=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h2>What is The Least Common Multiple (LCM)?</h2>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-4fd4db8d elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"4fd4db8d" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>The Least Common Multiple (LCM) is the smallest or least common=
 multiple that two or more numbers have in common.</p><p>Finding the LCM he=
lps us determine a common reference point for the given numbers together, m=
aking it easier to perform operations and solve problems involving multiple=
 quantities.</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-5f0deac2 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"5f0deac2" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h2>How to Find The Least Common Multiple (LCM)?</h2>								</div=
>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-4fa5105 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"4fa5105" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Finding the Least Common Multiple, or LCM, is like looking for =
a special number that can play nicely with a group of other numbers. We see=
k to find the least common multiple (LCM)=E2=80=94 the smallest number that=
 all your chosen numbers can divide evenly into, without leaving anything b=
ehind (like a remainder or a fraction).</p><p>But how do we find this frien=
dly number? Here are one to six prime factor methods, to calculate the leas=
t common multiple (LCM of two numbers):</p><ol><li><strong>Listing the Mult=
iples Method</strong>: This method is about multiplying multiple integers, =
and writing out the most common multiples of each number and finding the fi=
rst one they all share.</li><li><strong>Prime Factorization</strong>: Here,=
 you break down each number into its basic building blocks (prime numbers) =
and use them to find the LCM.</li><li><strong>Using the Greatest Common Div=
isor (GCD)</strong>: First, find the GCD of your numbers. Then, use a simpl=
e formula: LCM(a, b) =3D (a =C3=97 b) / GCD(a, b).</li><li><strong>Using th=
e Cake Method (Ladder Method)</strong>: This visual method breaks numbers d=
own step-by-step, similar to a ladder. By repeatedly dividing by prime numb=
ers, you can find common factors and their multiples.</li><li><strong>Using=
 the Division Method</strong>: Start by dividing the given numbers with pri=
me numbers. Continue dividing until you reach a stage where all numbers bec=
ome 1, then multiply the divisors for the LCM.</li><li><strong>Using the Ve=
nn Diagram</strong>: By breaking numbers into prime factors and placing the=
m in intersecting circles, you can visually identify shared and unique fact=
ors, multiplying them together for the LCM.</li></ol><div>&nbsp;</div><p>Ch=
oose the method that makes the most sense to you, and you=E2=80=99ll have t=
he tools you need to find the LCM! Let=E2=80=99s look at the first (and pro=
bably the easiest) method to arrive at the LCM:</p><div>&nbsp;</div>							=
	</div>
