=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h3>1. How to Find LCM by Listing Multiples</h3>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-71140677 elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"71140677" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Think of the =E2=80=9CListing Multiples Method=E2=80=9D as a bi=
t like sorting out toys or candies by type or color. To start, you choose t=
he numbers you want to find the LCM for. As an example, let=E2=80=99s choos=
e 5 and 6.</p><p>The LCM is the smallest multiple of numbers that each one =
can make when you multiply it. It=E2=80=99s like counting by the same numbe=
r: if you pick 5, you=E2=80=99d then list the whole multiples of 5, 10, 15,=
 25, 35, and so on. If you also pick 6, you have 6, 12, 18, 24 and 30.</p>	=
							</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-c116728 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-image" data-id=3D"c116728" data-element_type=3D"widget=
" data-widget_type=3D"image.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
															<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"800" heigh=
t=3D"523" src=3D"https://www.smartick.com/lp/wp-content/uploads/01-1.webp" =
class=3D"attachment-large size-large wp-image-8788" alt=3D"">														=
	</div>
