						<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-32c24d6d elementor-=
widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"32c24d6d" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h3>2. How to Find LCM by Prime Factorization</h3>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-1801769e elementor-wi=
dget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"1801769e" data-element_type=
=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">In this second method, you can imagine=
 each number as a puzzle, and the prime factorization method is like taking=
 each puzzle apart to see its tiniest pieces. To find the LCM using the pri=
me factorization method, follow these steps:</p><ol><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 =
1 []"><strong>Break It Down</strong>: Start your math by breaking each numb=
er into its prime factors. It=E2=80=99s like seeing what tiny building bloc=
ks make up your number.</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>List the F=
actors</strong>: Write down all the prime factors of each number. Some numb=
ers might share some common multiples of prime factors, while others might =
have unique ones.</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Build Your LCM</=
strong>: To get the highest power of LCM, take the highest power of all the=
 other prime numbers and factors you listed. It=E2=80=99s like building a n=
ew puzzle using the most pieces from each of your original prime numbers to=
gether.</li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p>								</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-3775d27 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"3775d27" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h3>3. How to Find the LCM Using the Division Method</h3>								<=
/div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-9e716a9 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"9e716a9" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p>Think of the Division Method as a step-by-step journey where yo=
u and the numbers work together. Here=E2=80=99s how you travel this path:</=
p><p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image=
-8803 size-large" src=3D"https://www.smartick.com/lp/wp-content/uploads/05-=
1-1024x648.webp" alt=3D"" width=3D"1024" height=3D"648"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><o=
l><li><strong>Start Together</strong>: Place the two numbers you want to fi=
nd the LCM for side by side.</li><li><strong>Divide by the Smallest Prime</=
strong>: Begin by dividing them by the smallest prime number that can divid=
e at least one of the smaller prime numbers from below. Write the results b=
elow.</li><li><strong>If a number isn=E2=80=99t divisible</strong> by whate=
ver of smaller prime numbers that is the smallest prime, just carry it down=
 as is.</li><li><strong>Continue Dividing</strong>: Keep dividing the resul=
ting numbers evenly divisible by prime factorization into smaller numbers. =
Each time, carry down any number that=E2=80=99s not evenly divisible by pri=
me factorization into bigger numbers.</li><li><strong>Reach the End</strong=
>: Continue this process until you end up with all ones at the bottom.</li>=
<li><strong>Multiply for the LCM</strong>: The LCM is found by multiplying =
all the prime numbers you have calculated and used to divide.</li></ol>				=
				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-204c8ea elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"204c8ea" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<h3>4. How to Find LCM Using the Cake Method (Ladder Method)</h3>	=
							</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-8bb3476 elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"8bb3476" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">Picture the Cake Method as baking a sp=
ecial layered cake where each layer helps you get closer to your delicious =
LCM. Here=E2=80=99s your recipe:</p><p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><img loadin=
g=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-8806 size-large=
" src=3D"https://www.smartick.com/lp/wp-content/uploads/06-1-1024x443.webp"=
 alt=3D"" width=3D"1024" height=3D"443"></p><p data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">&nb=
sp;</p><ol><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Gather Your Ingredients</st=
rong>: Write the numbers you want to find the LCM for next to each other, l=
ike you=E2=80=99re setting up ingredients for baking.</li><li data-pm-slice=
=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Layer by Layer</strong>: Divide these numbers by a prim=
e number that can go into at least one of them. Write the results beneath t=
he last row of given numbers.</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>If a=
 number isn=E2=80=99t divisible</strong> by that prime, simply write it dow=
n unchanged.</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Add More Layers</stro=
ng>: Continue dividing the results by prime numbers, just like you=E2=80=99=
d build up layers of a cake. Each time you divide, you=E2=80=99re adding an=
other layer!</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Finish Your Cake:</st=
rong> When all your numbers have been reduced to 1, your cake is complete.<=
/li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []"><strong>Taste the LCM</strong>: Multiply a=
ll the prime numbers you used to divide, and you=E2=80=99ll get the LCM=E2=
=80=A6</li><li data-pm-slice=3D"1 1 []">It=E2=80=99s the <strong>sweet resu=
lt</strong> of your efforts!</li></ol><p>The Cake (or Ladder) Method is a f=
un, visual way of combining numbers layer by layer, until you end up with t=
he perfect LCM treat. Enjoy every step of the baking.</p>								</div>
