				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
									<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The GCF Division Method is li=
ke using a secret shortcut that both simplifies and speeds up the process o=
f finding the LCM. Here=E2=80=99s your guide to this shortcut:</span></p><o=
l start=3D"2"><li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>Start by =
determining</b><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> the next smallest number =
of Greatest Common Factor (GCF) of the two numbers you want to find the LCM=
 for. You find the GCF by firstly stating the product of prime factors for =
each number, list the prime factors that are common to the two numbers, and=
 multiply them together.</span></li><li><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> =
This is the biggest number that can divide both numbers whole (without leav=
ing a remainder).&nbsp;</span></li><li><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> U=
se the Formula: Once you have the GCF, you can use a straightforward formul=
a: LCM(a, b) =3D (a =C3=97 b) / GCF(a, b). This means you=E2=80=99ll multip=
ly the two numbers together and then divide by their GCF.</span></li></ol><=
p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"><strong>Results Time</strong>: The calc=
ulated result from the above calculation is your LCM.</span></p><p>By using=
 the GCF Division Method, you=E2=80=99re leaning on the relationship betwee=
n the LCM and GCF of two numbers. It=E2=80=99s a quicker path to the LCM, m=
aking math a bit more magical and much more efficient.</p><div>&nbsp;</div>=
								</div>
